Sure, here's an example of how Monte Carlo integration can be implemented in C++ to approximate the definite integral of a function:
```
#include <iostream>
#include <cstdlib>
#include <cmath>

double f(double x) {
    // function to integrate
    return x*x;
}

double monte_carlo_integration(double a, double b, int n) {
    double total = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        double x = ((double)rand() / RAND_MAX) * (b - a) + a;
        total += f(x);
    }
    double estimate = total / n * (b - a);
    return estimate;
}

int main() {
    double a = 0; // lower bound
    double b = 1; // upper bound
    int n = 10000; // number of random points
    double estimate = monte_carlo_integration(a, b, n);
    std::cout << "Estimate of the definite integral of f(x) from " << a << " to " << b << ": " << estimate << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```
This code will approximate the definite integral of f(x) = x^2 from 0 to 1 using 10000 random points. The function `monte_carlo_integration` takes 3 arguments : the lower bound of integration, upper bound of integration and number of random points. It returns the estimated value of the definite integral.

Please note that the accuracy of the estimate will depend on the number of random points used and the function being integrated. In general, larger number of points will provide a more accurate estimate.
